</div>
	<div class="main">
		<div class="main-content">
			<div class="book-header">
				<div class="vers-view-type">
					<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/7012?vers_inline=1"><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946im_/http://catholicbible.online/assets/img/para.jpg" alt=""/></a>					<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/7012?comments_open=1"><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946im_/http://catholicbible.online/assets/img/C-off.gif" alt=""/></a>				</div>
				<div class="bible-name">The Holy Bible – Knox Translation</div>
				<div class="book-name">The Book of Deuteronomy </div>
				<div class="act-chapter">
					<div class="prev-chapter"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/7011">&lt; prev</a></div>|
					<div class="chapter">Chapter 21</div>
					|<div class="next-chapter"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/7013">next &gt;</a></div>
				</div>
				<div class="chapters">
					<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_1">1</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_2">2</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_3">3</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_4">4</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_5">5</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_6">6</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_7">7</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_8">8</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_9">9</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_10">10</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_11">11</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_12">12</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_13">13</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_14">14</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_15">15</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_16">16</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_17">17</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_18">18</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_19">19</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_20">20</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_21" class="active">21</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_22">22</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_23">23</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_24">24</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_25">25</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_26">26</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_27">27</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_28">28</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_29">29</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_30">30</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_31">31</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_32">32</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_33">33</a> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220812124946/http://catholicbible.online/knox/OT/Dt/ch_34">34</a> 				</div>
			</div>
						<div class="verses">
									<div id="vers149844" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">1</div>
						<div class="vers-content">When, in this land of thine, a dead man’s body is found and there is no knowing who slew him,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149845" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">2</div>
						<div class="vers-content">elders and judges must betake themselves to the spot where he lies, and find by measurement which of the neighbouring cities is nearest at hand.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149846" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">3</div>
						<div class="vers-content">It is for the elders of the nearest city to do what must be done. They will choose out from the herd a heifer that has never borne yoke or ploughed furrow,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149847" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">4</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and in some wild and rugged glen, that was never ploughed or sown, this heifer must have its neck broken.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149848" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">5</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Priests must be there, of Levi’s race; these are the men whom the Lord thy God has chosen to minister to him, and give their blessing in his name, and also to decide between right and wrong, clean and unclean.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149849" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">6</div>
						<div class="vers-content">And the elders of this neighbouring city, close to the dead man,<a href="" class="inline-comment" data-comment-id="326">✻</a> will wash their hands over the heifer that lies slain in the glen,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149850" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">7</div>
						<div class="vers-content">protesting, Not ours the hand that shed this blood; our eyes never witnessed the deed;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149851" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">8</div>
						<div class="vers-content">be merciful, Lord, to Israel, the people thou hast claimed for thyself; do not charge Israel, thy own people, with guilt because it is stained with an innocent man’s blood. So shall they be quit of all blame for the murder.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149852" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">9</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Do my bidding, and the guilt of blood wrongfully shed shall never rest upon thee.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149853" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">10</div>
						<div class="vers-content">When the Lord gives thee victory over thy enemies in battle, and thou bringest back prisoners,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149854" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">11</div>
						<div class="vers-content">dost thou see among them a woman so fair that she wins thy heart, and thou wouldst marry her?</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149855" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">12</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Take her, then, into thy house; and there she must shave her head and pare her nails close,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149856" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">13</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and lay aside the garb of a captive, that she wore till now. Let her have a month, dwelling in thy house, to bewail the loss of her father and mother; then thou mayest take her to thy bed and make her thy wife.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149857" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">14</div>
						<div class="vers-content">But if, afterwards, she does not answer thy mood, she must go free; thou hast no power to sell her or exercise lordship over her, when once thou hast robbed her of maidenhood.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149858" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">15</div>
						<div class="vers-content">If a man twice married loves one wife and is weary of the other, and has children by both, but his first-born by the wife he spurns,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149859" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">16</div>
						<div class="vers-content">how shall he divide up his possessions between them? He shall have no power to make the son of the loved wife his heir, in preference to that other.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149860" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">17</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Recognize the first-born he must, though of the mother he be weary; a double share of all his goods belongs to the son that was engendered first; the birthright is his.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149861" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">18</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Is there a son so rebellious and unmanageable that he defies his parents’ bidding, and will not brook restraint?</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149862" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">19</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Such a son they must bring by force to the city gate, where the elders are assembled,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149863" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">20</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and make complaint to them, This son of ours is rebellious and unmanageable; he pays no heed to our remonstrances, but must ever be carousing, ever at his wantonness and his cups.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149864" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">21</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Thereupon the citizens shall stone him to death, so that you may be rid of this plague, and every Israelite that hears of it may be afraid to do the like.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149865" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">22</div>
						<div class="vers-content">When a man is guilty of a capital crime, and his sentence is to hang on a gallows,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers149866" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">23</div>
						<div class="vers-content">his body must not be left to hang there on the gibbet, it must be buried the same day. God’s curse lies on the man who hangs on a gibbet, and the land which the Lord thy God gives thee for thy own must not suffer pollution.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
							</div>
			<div class="book-footer">
